# HTML & CSS — **Everything** you need for the exam (thorough, no sugar-coating)

Buckle up. Below you get a full explanation — what each element/property does, examples you can copy into the exam, common pitfalls, and a compact cheat-sheet at the end. I’ll be blunt: learn the box model and specificity — everything else is details you can memorize quickly.

---

# 1) Basic HTML structure (skeleton)

```html
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1" />
  <title>Document title</title>
  <!-- CSS -->
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
  <style> /* optional internal CSS */ </style>
</head>
<body>
  <header>Site header / logo / nav</header>
  <nav>Navigation links</nav>
  <main>
    <article>
      <h1>Heading</h1>
      <p>Paragraph text <a href="#">link</a>.</p>
      <img id="hero" src="image.jpg" alt="descriptive text">
    </article>
    <aside>Sidebar</aside>
  </main>
  <footer>Footer content / copyright</footer>
  <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

**Notes**

* `<!doctype html>`: triggers standards mode.
* `head` contains metadata, CSS links, scripts (preferably at bottom of `body` for performance unless `defer` or `async` used).
* Use semantic elements (`header`, `main`, `article`, `section`, `aside`, `footer`) for accessibility and SEO.

