# 2) Core HTML tags you must know (with purpose & quick example)

* **`<p>`** — paragraph
  `<p>This is a paragraph.</p>`

* **`<a>`** — anchor/link
  `<a href="https://example.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Visit</a>`
  `rel="noopener"` when opening new tabs for security.

* **`<div>`** — generic block container (non-semantic)
  `<div class="card">...</div>`

* **`<br>`** — line break (use sparingly; not for spacing layout)
  `Line one<br>Line two`

* **`<img>`** — image (self-closing in XHTML; HTML uses `<img>`):
  `<img src="pic.jpg" alt="description" width="300" height="200">`
  `alt` is mandatory for accessibility.

* **Text formatting**:

  * `<b>` — stylistic bold (use `<strong>` for importance/semantic emphasis).
  * `<strong>` — semantic importance (screen readers emphasize).
  * `<i>` — italic style.
  * `<em>` — semantic emphasis (often rendered as italic).
  * `<u>` — underline.
  * `<small>` — smaller text.
  * `<mark>` — highlighted text.
  * `<code>`, `<pre>` — code and preformatted text (preserve whitespace).
  * `<sub>`, `<sup>` — subscript, superscript.

* **Inline vs Block elements**

  * Inline: `<a>`, `<span>`, `<img>`, `<b>`, `<i>` — they flow inside text.
  * Block: `<div>`, `<p>`, `<header>`, `<section>` — take full width by default and stack vertically.

