# 3) CSS fundamentals

## 3.1 Selectors (how you target elements)

```css
/* element selector */ p { ... }
/* class selector */ .card { ... }
/* id selector */ #hero { ... }
/* descendant */ .nav a { ... }
/* child */ main > article { ... }
/* attribute */ input[type="text"] { ... }
/* pseudo-class */ a:hover { ... }
/* pseudo-element */ p::first-line { ... }
```

**Specificity (short)**: inline styles > IDs > classes/attributes/pseudo-classes > elements/pseudo-elements.
Calculate to resolve conflicts — exam favorite.

## 3.2 Box model (must know)

Content —> Padding —> Border —> Margin

* `width`/`height` — size of content box by default.
* `padding` — inner space (inside border).
* `border` — line around padding (visible).
* `margin` — outer spacing to other elements.

**box-sizing**:

```css
/* recommended */
* { box-sizing: border-box; }
```

`border-box` makes `width` include padding & border (easier to reason about).

## 3.3 Display types

* `display: block;` — full-width box, new line. (`div`, `p`)
* `display: inline;` — flows with text, width/height ignored.
* `display: inline-block;` — inline but accepts width/height & padding.
* `display: none;` — element removed from layout (no space).
* `visibility: hidden;` — hidden but occupies space.
* `display: flex;` — flex container (powerful layout).
* `display: grid;` — grid container.
* `display: table` / `table-cell` etc. — table-like layout.

## 3.4 Common layout properties

* `width`, `height` — can use `px`, `%`, `em`, `rem`, `vh`, `vw`, `auto`.
* `max-width`, `min-width`, `max-height`.
* `margin`: `margin: 10px 20px;` (top-bottom left-right shorthand)
  `margin-left: 10px;` or `margin: 0 auto;` (centers block horizontally when width set)
* `padding`: like margin.
* `float` — old layout technique (try to avoid for modern layouts).
* `position`: `static`, `relative`, `absolute`, `fixed`, `sticky` — controls flow & stacking.
* `z-index` — stacking order (works when `position` not `static`).

